aDLCbengerdacDLCdBTCTAdKENdNTEdOCLCFdGPOdOCLCQdOCLCAdFDSdFUGdOCLCAdOCLdDKCdOCLCQdOCLCLdOCLCOdGPO  apcc  aGPOO00aKF27b.B3 1967f  a10130 aY 4.B 22/1:EX 7/10/9671 aUnited States.bCongress.bHouse.bCommittee on Banking and Currency,eauthor.10aTo amend the Export-Import Bank act of 1945 :bHearings before the Committee on Banking and Currency, House of Representatives, Ninetieth Congress, first session, on H.R. 6649 a bill to amend the Export-Import Bank Act of 1945, as amended, to shorten the name of the Bank, to extend for five years the period within which the Bank is authorized to exercise its functions, to increase the Bank's lending authority and its authority to issue, against fractional reserves, export credit insurance and guarantees, and for other purposes. April 11, 12, and 28, 1967. 1aWashington, DC :bUnited States Government Printing Office,c1967.  aiii, 144 pages ;c23 cm  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aCover title.3 aShips have always played an important role in shaping human destiny, ranging from the Golden Hind to the HMS Beagle to the USS Indianapolis, and this comprehensive and very readable encyclopedia covers more than one thousand of the world's best known and most significant vessels of every size and type. Each ship is described in a vivid short essay that captures its personality as well as its physical characteristics, construction, and history, from the drawing board to the scrap yard or museum. Even fictional ships and boats, such as the African Queen, are included, whilst chronologies offer a perspective on underwater archaeological sites, naval warfare, maritime technology exploration, and disasters at sea. Ships of the World is not only an invaluable reference but fascinating reading for anyone who has the slightest interest in history or who simply likes messing about in boats, whether on the water or from a comfortable chair at home.10aUnited States.tExport-Import Bank Act of 1945.20aExport-Import Bank of Washington.27aExport-Import Bank of Washington2fast1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39QH7Jmqh86WcvbKdwv9km7TR0(OCoLC)fst00537324 7aLegislative hearings2fast0(OCoLC)fst019108251 aUnited States.bCongress.n(90th, 1st session :d1967).bHouse.08iOnline version:aUnited States. Congress. House. Committee on Banking and Currency.tTo amend the Export-Import Bank act of 1945.w(OCoLC)691759502  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 759; HSL003; 20260415  aHistoric Shelflist; BC29; bca16c20091202  aZAI84c2016062702817cam a2200493 i 00064102320260415105532.0770429s1967    dcu          f000 0 eng    a67062605  a1018813  a(OCoLC)2928344z(OCoLC)1018813  aUTLbengerdacUTLdCSUdOCLdOCLCQdCDSdNTEdOCLCQdOCLCOdOCLCFdOCLCQdWAUdGPOdONBdOCLCAdFDSdFUGdOCLCAdOCLdOCLCQdOCLCOdOCLdOCLCOdOCLCLdGPO  apcc  an-us---  aGPOO 4aKF968.8b.B32 1967d  a10130 a332.1/541https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/ddc/E3vjmw4H9vdhkj8FW76X8qHbHY0 aY 4.B 22/1:EX 7/10/967-21 aUnited States.bCongress.bHouse.bCommittee on Banking and Currency,eauthor.10aTo amend the Export-Import Bank Act of 1945--supplemental hearings :bhearings before the Committee on Banking and Currency, House of Representatives, Ninetieth Congress, first session, on H.R. 6649, a bill to amend the Export-Import Bank Act of 1945, as amended, to shorten the name of the Bank, to extend for five years the period within which the Bank is authorized to exercise its functions, to increase the Bank's lending authority to issue, against fractional reserves, export credit insurance and guarantees, and for other purposes. September 12 and 13, 1967. 1aWashington, 